<section id="what-is-fengshui">
      <h2>What Is Feng Shui?</h2>

      <div class="image-panel">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1741354563315-d28f7aa63cf5?w=1200&h=400&fit=crop" alt="Misty Chinese mountain landscape with river — embodying feng shui principles of wind and water" loading="lazy">
        <div class="image-panel-caption">
          <h3>Wind &amp; Water</h3>
          <p>The ancient art of reading landscapes to harmonise people with natural forces</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Feng Shui (<span class="chinese-char">風水</span>, literally "wind-water") is the traditional Chinese system of geomancy &mdash; the art and science of assessing landscapes to understand how natural energy (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>, Qi) flows through them.</p>

      <div class="quote-card">
        <p>Qi rides the wind and scatters, but is retained when encountering water.</p>
        <cite><em>Zangshu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">葬書</span>, Book of Burial) &mdash; the foundational principle of all Feng Shui</cite>
      </div>

      <div class="stat-highlight">
        <span class="stat-highlight-number">3,500+</span>
        <div class="stat-highlight-text"><strong>Years</strong> of continuous practice — from Shang Dynasty burial siting to Song Dynasty imperial city planning. Not interior decorating, but a rigorous discipline of land assessment.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="historical-origins">
      <h2>Historical Origins</h2>
      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">Shang Dynasty (c. 1600-1046 BCE)</div>
          <h4>Earliest Evidence</h4>
          <p>Burial sites show careful orientation according to cardinal directions and terrain.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">Jin Dynasty (266-420 CE)</div>
          <h4>Guo Pu (<span class="chinese-char">郭璞</span>) &mdash; Zangshu</h4>
          <p>Systematised burial geomancy principles, articulating how landforms determine Qi flow.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">Tang Dynasty</div>
          <h4>Yang Yunsong (<span class="chinese-char">楊筠松</span>) &mdash; Form School</h4>
          <p>Imperial geomancer who founded the Form School in Jiangxi. Authored <em>Hanlongjing</em> and <em>Yilongjing</em> on tracing dragon veins.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">Song Dynasty</div>
          <h4>Compass School Matures</h4>
          <p>Flying Stars (Xuan Kong) developed, Luopan refined. Feng Shui became integral to imperial city planning.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="form-school">
      <h2>The Form School (<span class="chinese-char">巒頭派</span>)</h2>
      <p>The Form School reads the physical landscape directly &mdash; mountains, rivers, terrain contours. Central is the concept of <strong>dragon veins</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">龍脈</span>): ridges along which Qi flows from distant peaks to the <strong>dragon's lair</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">龍穴</span>).</p>

      <div class="info-grid">
        <div class="info-card">
          <span class="info-card-icon">🐲</span>
          <div class="info-card-value">Azure Dragon</div>
          <div class="info-card-label">East (<span class="chinese-char">青龍</span>)</div>
          <div class="info-card-desc">Hills to the left (facing south), slightly higher, representing protective yang energy.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <span class="info-card-icon">🐅</span>
          <div class="info-card-value">White Tiger</div>
          <div class="info-card-label">West (<span class="chinese-char">白虎</span>)</div>
          <div class="info-card-desc">Terrain to the right, lower and subdued. If higher than the Dragon, the site is inauspicious.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <span class="info-card-icon">🐢</span>
          <div class="info-card-value">Black Tortoise</div>
          <div class="info-card-label">North (<span class="chinese-char">玄武</span>)</div>
          <div class="info-card-desc">Mountain behind, providing solid backing and shielding from northern winds.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <span class="info-card-icon">🐦</span>
          <div class="info-card-value">Vermilion Bird</div>
          <div class="info-card-label">South (<span class="chinese-char">朱雀</span>)</div>
          <div class="info-card-desc">Open space in front, allowing Qi to gather in the "bright hall" (<span class="chinese-char">明堂</span>).</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="compass-school">
      <h2>The Compass School (<span class="chinese-char">理氣派</span>)</h2>
      <p>The Compass School introduces mathematical precision using the <strong>Luopan</strong> compass. It maps invisible energies of compass directions, trigram sectors, and temporal cycles.</p>
      <p>The <strong>Eight Trigrams</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">八卦</span>) form the backbone of directional analysis. Derived from the Yijing, the trigrams &mdash; Qian, Kun, Zhen, Xun, Kan, Li, Gen, Dui &mdash; each govern a direction with specific elemental and symbolic associations.</p>
      <p>The most sophisticated method is <strong>Xuan Kong Feixing</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">玄空飛星</span>, Flying Stars), which assigns shifting numerical values to directional sectors according to 20-year, annual, and monthly cycles. This allows practitioners to assess when a site's energies peak and decline.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="luopan">
      <h2>The Luopan Compass</h2>
      <p>The Luopan (<span class="chinese-char">羅盤</span>) is a portable encyclopaedia of Chinese cosmology. At its centre lies the <strong>Heaven Pool</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">天池</span>) &mdash; a magnetic needle pointing to magnetic south. Radiating outward are concentric rings containing:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>24 Mountains (<span class="chinese-char">二十四山</span>)</strong> &mdash; 24 sectors of 15 degrees each, combining Earthly Branches, Heavenly Stems, and trigrams.</li>
        <li><strong>Trigram rings</strong> &mdash; Earlier Heaven and Later Heaven arrangements for different analytical purposes.</li>
        <li><strong>Stems and Branches</strong> &mdash; Various combinations for temporal and directional calculations.</li>
        <li><strong>28 Lunar Mansions</strong> &mdash; Correlating terrestrial directions with celestial constellations.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="imperial">
      <h2>Feng Shui in Imperial China</h2>
      <div class="image-grid image-grid--3">
        <figure>
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1716929955955-f6ef9c1ca084?w=400&h=300&fit=crop" alt="The Great Wall of China stretching across mountains" loading="lazy">
          <figcaption>Forbidden City &mdash; geomantic perfection</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1739475837710-d74d97fdb520?w=400&h=300&fit=crop" alt="Traditional Chinese porcelain art from the Ming Dynasty" loading="lazy">
          <figcaption>Ming Tombs &mdash; horseshoe valley</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1759046263120-763faa804cf8?w=400&h=300&fit=crop" alt="Traditional Chinese garden pavilion with mountain backdrop" loading="lazy">
          <figcaption>Chang'an &mdash; Qinling Mountains backing</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
      <p>The <strong>Forbidden City</strong> sits on a north-south axis with Jingshan Hill behind (Black Tortoise), Tiananmen Square to the south (bright hall), and the Golden Water River curving in a jade-belt formation. The <strong>Ming Tombs</strong> valley — a horseshoe of mountains with a watercourse through the south — shelters thirteen emperors. <strong>Chang'an</strong> and <strong>Luoyang</strong> were systematic geomantic selections at the highest imperial level.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="five-elements">
      <h2>Five Elements in Feng Shui</h2>
      <p>The <a href="/wuxing/">Five Elements</a> provide the language for describing how Qi manifests. In the Form School, landscape shapes encode elements: pointed peaks are Fire, flat tops are Earth, rounded hills Metal, undulations Water, tall formations Wood.</p>
      <p>In the Compass School, each trigram sector carries an element: Kan (north) is Water, Li (south) Fire, Zhen/Xun are Wood, Qian/Dui are Metal, Gen/Kun are Earth. The interaction between a building's direction and these sectors determines energy quality.</p>
    </section>

